{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525137"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:12:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14061"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14061"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.24,0.4,0.05,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6715"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14061"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40707"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"761"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2792"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16882"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of right lower quadrant pain. She has a medical history of hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her regular medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals mild right lower quadrant tenderness without guarding or rebound. A CT scan of the chest and abdomen is performed as part of the diagnostic workup.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe radiologist reports an incidental finding as seen below (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management regarding this incidental finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent surgical repair","Elective surgical repair","Conservative management with follow-up imaging","Chest tube insertion","Referral to cardiothoracic surgery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe incidental finding described in this patient\u0027s CT scan is consistent with a Bochdalek hernia, a congenital diaphragmatic hernia typically found on the left side. In this case, the hernia contains the left kidney and spleen, which is a common presentation for this type of hernia. It\u0027s important to note that this finding is incidental and unrelated to the patient\u0027s presenting complaint of right lower quadrant pain, which requires separate evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management with follow-up imaging\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step for this incidental finding. In adults, Bochdalek hernias are often asymptomatic and discovered incidentally during imaging studies for other conditions. If the patient is asymptomatic from the hernia, immediate surgical intervention is not necessary. Regular follow-up imaging can be used to monitor the hernia for any changes or complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent surgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if the patient were experiencing acute symptoms related to the hernia, such as bowel obstruction or respiratory distress. However, this patient\u0027s symptoms  seem to be unrelated to her hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective surgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered in the future if the patient develops symptoms related to the hernia or if there are concerns about potential complications. However, it is not the immediate next step for an asymptomatic incidental finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest tube insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for a Bochdalek hernia. This procedure is typically used for conditions such as pneumothorax or pleural effusion, not for diaphragmatic hernias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to cardiothoracic surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step for an asymptomatic incidental Bochdalek hernia. While cardiothoracic surgeons may be involved in the surgical management of complex diaphragmatic hernias, immediate referral is not necessary for an asymptomatic incidental finding. Conservative management with follow-up is more appropriate at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s crucial to emphasize that while managing this incidental finding, the patient\u0027s presenting symptom of right lower quadrant pain should be thoroughly investigated, as it is likely unrelated to the Bochdalek hernia and could be due to other conditions such as appendicitis, diverticulitis, or ovarian pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bochdalek hernias are congenital diaphragmatic hernias typically found on the left side.","Incidental Bochdalek hernias in adults are often asymptomatic and do not require immediate surgical intervention.","CT imaging is the gold standard for diagnosing Bochdalek hernias, showing herniation of abdominal contents into the thoracic cavity."],"references":["Dingeldein M. Congenital Diaphragmatic Hernia: Management \u0026 Outcomes. Adv Pediatr 2018; 65:241-47. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30053927/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40707"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14061"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20945"},{"type":"media","id":"20946"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21084"},{"type":"media","id":"21085"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20945"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/pAsqBVgLzCI1shhUoG33agovU6lEal.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/pAsqBVgLzCI1shhUoG33agovU6lEal.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":512,"height":512}},{"type":"media","id":"20946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20946"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/S87FkKh1RdlZjqxNEfP2HsXe0Vyd0D.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/S87FkKh1RdlZjqxNEfP2HsXe0Vyd0D.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":584,"height":584}},{"type":"media","id":"21084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21084"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0Bj4E8nZafXsVGuMljXSS0q6YWLAHc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0Bj4E8nZafXsVGuMljXSS0q6YWLAHc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":512,"height":512}},{"type":"media","id":"21085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21085"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/LDD5Cezf5XMHCnXuSqHXwhJMN6RElR.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/LDD5Cezf5XMHCnXuSqHXwhJMN6RElR.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":584,"height":584}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40707"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T22:42:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T22:43:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6715"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":fa